The '''Royal Game of Ur''', also known as the '''Game of Twenty Squares''' or simply the '''Game of Ur''', is a [[Two-player game|two-player]] [[Strategy game|strategy]] [[Race game|race]] [[board game]] that was first played in ancient [[Mesopotamia]] during the early third millennium BC. The game was popular across the Middle East among people of all social strata and boards for playing it have been found at locations as far away from Mesopotamia as [[Crete]] and [[Sri Lanka]]. At the height of its popularity, the game acquired spiritual significance, and events in the game were believed to reflect a player's future and convey messages from deities or other supernatural beings. The Game of Ur remained popular until [[late antiquity]], when it stopped being played, possibly evolving into, or being displaced by, an early form of [[backgammon]]. It was eventually forgotten everywhere except among the [[Cochin Jews|Jewish population]] of the Indian city of [[Kochi]], who continued playing a version of it until the 1950s when they began [[Aliyah|emigrating]] to [[Israel]].

The Game of Ur received its name because it was first rediscovered by the English archaeologist [[Leonard Woolley|Sir Leonard Woolley]] during his excavations of the [[Royal Cemetery at Ur]] between 1922 and 1934. Copies of the game have since been found by other archaeologists across the Middle East. The rules of the Game of Ur as it was played in the second century BC have been preserved on a Babylonian clay tablet written by the scribe Itti-Marduk-balālu. Based on this tablet and the shape of the {{boardgloss|gameboard}}, [[British Museum]] curator [[Irving Finkel]] has reconstructed the basic rules of how the game might have been played. The object of the game is to run the course of the board and bear all one's pieces off before one's opponent. Like modern backgammon, the game combines elements of both strategy and random chance.

==History==
[[File:bm-royalgame.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|A [[graffito (archaeology)|graffito]] version of the game from the palace of [[Sargon II]] (British Museum in London){{sfn|Collon|2011}}{{sfn|Green|2008}}]]

The Game of Ur was popular across the Middle East{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=25}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} and boards for it have been found in [[Iran]], [[Syria]], Egypt, [[Lebanon]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Cyprus]], and [[Crete]].{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=25}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} Four gameboards bearing a very close resemblance to the Royal Game of Ur were found in the funeral chamber of the [[KV62|Tomb of Tutankhamun]].{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} These boards came with small boxes to store dice and game pieces{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} and many had [[senet]] boards on the reverse sides so that the same board could be used to play either game and merely had to be flipped over.{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} The game was popular among all social classes.{{sfn|Green|2008}} A [[Graffito (archaeology)|graffito]] version of the game carved with a sharp object, possibly a dagger, was discovered on one of the [[Shedu|human-headed winged bull]] gate sentinels from the palace of [[Sargon II]] (721–705 BC) in the city of [[Khorsabad]].{{sfn|Collon|2011}}{{sfn|Green|2008}}

The Game of Ur eventually acquired superstitious significance{{sfn|Donovan|2017|pages=14–15}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} and the tablet of Itti-Marduk-balālu provides vague predictions for the players' futures if they land on certain spaces,{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=14}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} such as "You will find a friend", "You will become powerful like a lion", or "You will draw fine beer".{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=14}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} People saw relationships between a player's success in the game and his or her success in real life.{{sfn|Donovan|2017|pages=15–16}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} Seemingly random events such as landing on a certain square were interpreted as messages from deities, ghosts of deceased ancestors, or from a person's own soul.{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=16}}

It is unclear what led to the Game of Ur's eventual decline during late antiquity.{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=16}} One theory holds that it evolved into [[backgammon]];{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=16}} whereas another holds that early forms of backgammon eclipsed the Game of Ur in popularity, causing players to eventually forget about the older game.{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=16}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} At some point before the game fell out of popularity in the Middle East, it was apparently introduced to the Indian city of [[Kochi]] by a group of Jewish merchants.{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=16}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} Members of the [[Cochin Jews|Jewish population of Kochi]] were still playing a recognizable form of the Game of Ur by the time they started [[Aliyah|emigrating]] to [[Israel]] in the 1950s after [[World War II]].{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=16}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} The Kochi version of the game had twenty squares, just like the original Mesopotamian version,{{sfn|Green|2008}} but each player had twelve pieces rather than seven{{sfn|Green|2008}} and the placement of the twenty squares was slightly different.{{sfn|Green|2008}}

==Modern rediscovery==
The British archaeologist [[Leonard Woolley|Sir Leonard Woolley]] discovered five gameboards of the Game of Ur during his excavation of the [[Royal Cemetery at Ur]] between 1922 and 1934.{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=16}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}}{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=13}} Because the game was first discovered in the Royal Cemetery at Ur, it became known as the "Royal Game of Ur",{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=13}} but later archaeologists uncovered other copies of the game from various other locations across the Middle East.{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=13}} Each of the boards discovered by Wooley date to around 3000 BC.{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=16}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=713}} All five boards were of an identical type,{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=16}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} but they were made of different materials and had different decorations.{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=16}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} Woolley reproduced images of two of these boards in his 1949 book, ''The First Phases''.{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=16}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} One of these is a relatively simple set with a background composed of discs of shell with blue or red centers set in wood-covered [[bitumen]].{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=16}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} The other is a more elaborate one completely covered with shell plaques, inlaid with red [[limestone]] and [[lapis lazuli]].{{sfn|Bell|1979|pages=16–17}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} Other gameboards are often engraved with images of animals.{{sfn|Bell|1979|page=17}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}}{{sfn|Green|2008}}

==Gameplay==

===Reconstruction===
[[File:Royal Game of Ur rules.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Rules tablet|Rules tablet dated 177 BC (British Museum ref:{{British-Museum-db|33333,b|id=796973}})]]

When the Game of Ur was first discovered, no one knew how it was played.{{sfn|Finkel|2007|page=16}}{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=14}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}}{{sfn|Bell|1979|pages=16–19}} Then, in the early 1980s, [[Irving Finkel]], a curator at the [[British Museum]], translated a clay tablet written {{circa}} 177 BC by the Babylonian scribe Itti-Marduk-balālu describing how the game was played during that time period, based on an earlier description of the rules by another scribe named Iddin-Bēl.{{sfn|Finkel|2007|page=16}}{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=14}} This tablet was written during the waning days of Babylonian civilization,{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=14}} long after the time when the Game of Ur was first played.{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}} It had been discovered in 1880 in the ruins of Babylon and sold to the British Museum.{{sfn|Finkel|2007|page=16}} Finkel also used photographs of another tablet describing the rules, which had been in the personal collection of Count Aymar de Liedekerke-Beaufort, but had been destroyed during [[World War I]].{{sfn|Finkel|2007|page=16}} This second tablet was undated, but is believed by archaeologists to have been written several centuries earlier than the tablet by Itti-Marduk-balālu and to have originated from the city of [[Uruk]].{{sfn|Finkel|2007|page=16}} The backs of both tablets show diagrams of the gameboard, clearly indicating which game they are describing.{{sfn|Finkel|2007|page=16}}{{sfn|Green|2008}} Based on these rules and the shape of the gameboard, Finkel was able to reconstruct how the game might have been played.{{sfn|Finkel|2007|page=16}}{{sfn|Donovan|2017|page=14}}{{sfn|Botermans|2008|page=712}}

===Basic rules===
